t merely a convenient shorthand, but productive tools for creating order amid the chaos of early nineteenth-century organic chemistry. With these formulas, chemists could create a multifaceted world on paper, which they then correlated with experiments and the traces produced in test tubes and flasks. The author’s semiotic approach to the formulas allows her to show in detail how their particular semantic and representational qualities made them especially useful as paper tools for productive application.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSCIENCE / Chemistry / Organic.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361983840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503619838423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503619838/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles